178abf5b-bc99-4b01-b1d8-b3e581d90e9d.57977f64-8a98-4751-813c-41dfffb18213.description=
Runs a SQL command against an Oracle database, using the information available in the tnsnames.ora file.   
Does not return any results (only whether the command was executed)

Input Parameters\:
TNSPath - The path to the parent folder of the TNS file which contains the DB connecting info(the name of the DB server, the port used for connecting to the DB server, the database name)
TNSEntry - the entry name from the tnsnames.ora file which contains the connecting information
Username - username to connect as
Password - password
Command - the command to execute

Responses\:
more items - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
updateCount - the update count of the command executed

NOTE\: 
This op supports only Oracle. The tnsnames.ora file should correctly configured on the RAS machine.

ORACLE NOTE\:
It is possible to run PL/SQL procedures using this operation. The examples below present the syntax to be used for having the same effect as the following PL/SQL script\:
BEGIN
  send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');
END;

Example 1\: BEGIN send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');END;

Example 2\: BEGIN send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test');END;

Example 3\: {CALL send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test')}

Example 4\: {CALL send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test')}

Inputs\: _PROCESS_INSTANCE_ID - Process Instance Id _processInstanceState - Process Instance State (Use value from selection list CSA-ProcessInstance-State) Result\: _processInstanceState -Updated Process Instance State 178abf5b-bc99-4b01-b1d8-b3e581d90e9d.9054a2e2-7cd3-4fec-902e-ff8cda793f94.description=
Schedules a flow or updates an existing schedule of a flow. The operation can be used on OO version 9.03 and greater.  

Inputs\:
    host - The host running Central 9.03 or greater.
Default value\: localhost.
    username - The username to use when connecting to the Central service.
    password - The password to use when connecting to the Central service.
    port - The port the Central service is running on.
Default value\: 8443.
    protocol - Either http or https. The protocol used to communicate to the Central service.
Default value\: https.
    trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false.
    trustKeystore - The path of the truststore file. It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used. If not specified  the operation will search for{iconclude_home}/Central/conf/rc_keystore or {iconclude_home}/Studio/conf/rc_keystore in this order.
    trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore. Provide this input only if trustKeystore is not empty.
    flow - The uuid or the path of the flow to run.
Example\: /library/my ops flows/test
    schedule - The uuid of the schedule to update.
    names - A delimiter separated list of names of flow inputs.
    values - A delimiter separated list of values of flow inputs.
    delimiter - the delimiter separating lists of names and values.
    description - a description of this schedule.
    enabled - Set false to create the schedule disabled. This input is case insensitive.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: true.
    startTime - The time to start running the flow either as minutes from now or as a date. Use the utility operations from "Date and Time" folder to pass valid startTime value.
Example\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT
Example\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT+0430 (4 hours, 30 minutes west of the Greenwich meridian)
    endTime - The time to end running the flow either as minutes from now or as a date. Use the utility operations from "Date and Time" folder to pass valid endTime value.
Example\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT
Example\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT+0430 (4 hours, 30 minutes west of the Greenwich meridian)
    timesToRun - The number of times to re-run the flow schedule. If empty, the number of times to re-run the schedule will be computed as (endTime - startTime)/repeatInterval. If -1 the flow will be scheduled to run indefinitely, otherwise this input must have a positive value.
    repeatInterval - Sets the time Interval in minutes between schedule triggering. If empty, the operation will set it to 1 minute.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Primary output. The uuid of the schedule.
    flowUuid - The uuid of the flow. This can be useful if the flow input is the path of the flow.

Responses\:
    success -The schedule was created or updated.
    failure - Could not connect to central web service. Invalid inputs. Invalid flow path. The schedule ends before it starts. The schedule ends in the past.

Notes\:
1.  and  inputs are mutually exclusive.
2.  and  inputs are mutually exclusive.

For example\: Windows. osSPVersion - The service pack version of the OS running on the object. peerIP - The managed server's peer IP address. platformName - The name of the platform. previousSWRegDate -The last time the Opsware agent reported the installed software on the server. realmName - The name of the realm this object is in. stage - The stage of the managed server. state - The current state of the managed server\: OK, UNREACHABLE or MAINTENANCE use - The intended use of the managed server (i.e. its role in a deployment)\: DEVELOPMENT, STAGING, PRODUCTION or UNKNOWN. virtualizationType - The virtualization type. 178abf5b-bc99-4b01-b1d8-b3e581d90e9d.fcc8181c-e869-43f2-9ca5-4ccc57a8159e.description=
Offsets the current date and time by a given number of units. If locale is specified, the date and time will be in the format based on the locale. Otherwise, default locale will be used. 

Inputs\:
units - The number of units to offset by. If this is positive, the offset goes into the future, if it is negative the offset goes into the past.
secondsPerUnit - The number of seconds per unit. This defaults to 1 hour, thus the units is by default measured in hours.
localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. For example,  en or ja.
localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Returns\:
The offset date/time. 

Responses\:
success - Operation completed successfully.
failure - Something went wrong.
